{"name":"OWP Productivity Insights","version":"1.3","generated_at":"2026-04-29T19:01:30.788832+00:00","source":"cortex-mockup repo \u00b7 58 cortex output JSONs across 3 schema generations (v2.0/v2.1/v2.2) \u00b7 PROJECT_ORDER 71 closed jobs","cortex_layer":"productivity_insights","audience":"bid_model_calibration","usage_instructions":"Drives the bid intelligence tool calibration panel and the COST_CODES variance defaults. Regenerate via owp/build_calibration.py whenever a new closed job lands.","scope":{"total_jobs":71,"completed_jobs_in_benchmarks":58,"completed_with_unit_data":58,"live_jobs":0,"schemas_loaded":{"v2.2":20,"v2.1":17,"v2.0":21},"missing_data_jsons":["2001","2008","2009","2010","2011","2012","2015","2016","2017","2018","2019","2021","2022"]},"headline_findings":[{"id":"material_takeoff_systematically_conservative","severity":"high","title":"OWP material takeoffs systematically come in under original budget","value":-0.2511,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 58 completed jobs, the median material variance from original budget to actual spend is -25.1%. Negative means UNDER budget. This is the strongest single signal in the dataset for calibrating the bid model.","evidence":{"n_jobs":436,"p25":-0.4823,"median":-0.2511,"p75":-0.0163},"implication":"Two valid responses for the bid model: (a) tighten the takeoff factor by ~25% and bid a leaner number, or (b) hold the cushion as a declared margin contribution and report it explicitly to leadership. Without an explicit policy, this cushion compounds opaquely."},{"id":"roughin_labor_overruns","severity":"high","title":"Rough-in labor (code 120) is the major labor code that runs over budget","value":0.1014,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 58 completed jobs, code 120 (rough-in labor) has a median original\u2192actual variance of +10.1%. Most other major labor codes run UNDER budget. This means takeoff hours for rough-in are systematically too low.","evidence":{"code":"120","description":"Roughin Labor","n_jobs":58,"variance_orig_to_actual":{"n":58,"min":-0.3361,"max":1.0927,"mean":0.131,"median":0.1014,"p25":-0.1037,"p50":0.1014,"p75":0.2926,"p10":-0.2029,"p90":0.5106},"median_actual_dollars":244737.23},"implication":"Bid model should apply a +10\u201315% correction factor to rough-in labor takeoff specifically. Material cushion alone does not compensate for this \u2014 labor is harder to recover once underbid."},{"id":"hours_per_unit_house_standard","severity":"high","title":"House standard for labor productivity is ~119 hours per plumbing unit","value":118.7163,"unit":"hours","summary":"Median is 118.7 hrs/unit (P25 101, P75 143). The middle 50% of jobs sit between 101 and 143 hrs/unit \u2014 that is the credible band for a like-for-like new bid.","evidence":{"n":58,"min":57.375,"max":2400.0,"mean":163.589,"median":118.7163,"p25":100.963,"p50":118.7163,"p75":142.7872,"p10":75.1421,"p90":166.6574,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"implication":"Bids that fall below P25 or above P75 should be flagged for explicit justification \u2014 the bidding tool should not silently extrapolate beyond the historical band."},{"id":"gross_margin_band","severity":"medium","title":"Gross margin clusters at 38.4%","value":0.384,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Median gross margin is 38.4%. This is what OWP earns once direct cost (labor + material + burden + tax) is removed from billed revenue.","evidence":{"n_jobs":58,"p25":0.3119,"median":0.384,"p75":0.4537},"implication":"Use as default target margin. Combine with material-takeoff cushion finding for total margin posture."},{"id":"wage_burden","severity":"medium","title":"Fully loaded labor cost is ~$41.56/hr (1.42\u00d7 blended)","value":41.56,"unit":"USD/hr","summary":"Median fully loaded wage (labor + burden) is $41.56/hr. Burden multiplier of 1.42\u00d7 means OWP carries ~42% on top of direct wages for taxes, insurance, vehicles, etc.","evidence":{"blended_wage_median":28.9569,"loaded_wage_median":41.56,"burden_multiplier_median":1.4225},"implication":"Always price labor at fully-loaded wage in the bid model."},{"id":"labor_variance_neutral","severity":"medium","title":"Labor variance is roughly balanced (-15.7% median)","value":-0.1565,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Unlike material (consistently under), labor variance from original budget to actual is closer to neutral (median -15.7%). The bid model should NOT assume a labor cushion the way it can for material.","evidence":{"n":552,"min":-0.9914,"max":3.4135,"mean":-0.0957,"median":-0.1565,"p25":-0.4075,"p50":-0.1565,"p75":0.1064,"p10":-0.5976,"p90":0.4421},"implication":"Bid the labor number close to the takeoff \u2014 there is no systematic safety margin."}],"benchmarks":{"hours_per_unit":{"n":58,"min":57.375,"max":2400.0,"mean":163.589,"median":118.7163,"p25":100.963,"p50":118.7163,"p75":142.7872,"p10":75.1421,"p90":166.6574,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"labor_dollars_per_unit":{"n":58,"min":1419.3979,"max":90082.0,"mean":5141.0564,"median":3614.8673,"p25":2761.8499,"p50":3614.8673,"p75":4223.3833,"p10":1974.3037,"p90":5242.2541,"note":"Direct labor cost / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"material_dollars_per_unit":{"n":58,"min":1219.6971,"max":58415.81,"mean":4603.1711,"median":3529.9441,"p25":2889.0769,"p50":3529.9441,"p75":4214.4879,"p10":2075.5456,"p90":5078.2547,"note":"200-series cost code spend / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"revenue_per_unit":{"n":58,"min":7181.5,"max":350295.0,"mean":21271.1269,"median":15947.22,"p25":12461.7668,"p50":15947.22,"p75":17999.8866,"p10":10089.2293,"p90":19678.7883,"note":"999 sales code billed / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"labor_pct_of_revenue":{"n":58,"min":0.1089,"max":0.3355,"mean":0.2356,"median":0.2312,"p25":0.2099,"p50":0.2312,"p75":0.2715,"p10":0.185,"p90":0.2897,"note":"Labor cost / revenue","unit":"fraction"},"material_pct_of_revenue":{"n":58,"min":0.0936,"max":0.3135,"mean":0.2349,"median":0.2348,"p25":0.2166,"p50":0.2348,"p75":0.2643